{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652091"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18510"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18510"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.1,0.7,0.05,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78643"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11239"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63985"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7419"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26310"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78643"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe superior gluteal nerve is an important motor nerve that supplies muscles critical for hip abduction and pelvic stability during walking.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the course and distribution of the superior gluteal nerve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exits through the obturator canal to supply adductor muscles","Exits through the lesser sciatic foramen to supply hip rotators","Exits above piriformis to supply gluteus medius and minimus","Passes through the greater sciatic foramen to supply hamstring muscles","Passes below piriformis to supply gluteus maximus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe superior gluteal nerve demonstrates a specific anatomical pathway where it \u003Cstrong\u003Eexits above piriformis to supply gluteus medius and minimus\u003C/strong\u003E. After emerging superior to the piriformis muscle through the greater sciatic foramen, it provides motor innervation to three key muscles: gluteus medius, gluteus minimus, and tensor fasciae latae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding why the other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eexits through the obturator canal to supply adductor muscles\u003C/strong\u003E describes a different nerve entirely - the obturator nerve takes this path\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eexits through the lesser sciatic foramen to supply hip rotators\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this pathway is taken by the pudendal nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epasses through the greater sciatic foramen to supply hamstring muscles\u003C/strong\u003E describes the path of the sciatic nerve, which emerges inferior to piriformis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epasses below piriformis to supply gluteus maximus\u003C/strong\u003E actually describes the inferior gluteal nerve\u0027s course\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis nerve originates from posterior divisions of the L4, L5 and S1 nerve roots and plays a crucial role in maintaining stability of the pelvis when walking, particularly during the stance phase.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The gluteus medius, gluteus minimus, and tensor fasciae latae muscles receive innervation from the superior gluteal nerve.","The superior gluteal nerve emerges from the pelvis by passing through the greater sciatic foramen in a position superior to the piriformis.","Spinal nerve roots L4, L5 and S1 combine to form the superior gluteal nerve."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cPlan of sacral and pudendal plexuses\u201d by Henry Vandyke Carter is under\u00a0Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gray828.png"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63985"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18510"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21411"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21411"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tjbYR279UiWGrApe7u0T8EjjyVQ6xq.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tjbYR279UiWGrApe7u0T8EjjyVQ6xq.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":844}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63985"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T20:52:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T00:17:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11239"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78643"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, p